A great deal of interest is shown today in the activation of methane and higher alkanes. A number of complexes of transition metals of group 111-V, lanthanides and actinides have recently been reported to activate the C-H bond of alkanes and aromatic hydrocarbons. 1 A common feature of these complexes is that the metal is in its highest oxidation state; it therefore, has a do electron configuration and is consequently highly electrophilic. The first example of an intermolecular alkane activation reaction is the methyl exchange with methane in a lutetium complex, Scheme 1.2 We report here that a zirconium hydride complex, grafted onto the surface of silica, acquires such high electrophilic properties, that the reaction of o-bond metathesis between the Zr hydride and the C-H bonds of cyclooctane and methane becomes feasible.
